                            <comment id="43181" author="simmonsja" created="Tue, 14 Aug 2012 08:46:24 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;All fixed and merged. We can close this ticket now.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="42535" author="yong.fan" created="Tue, 31 Jul 2012 21:14:36 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks James for the the patches verifying!&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="42503" author="simmonsja" created="Tue, 31 Jul 2012 12:55:16 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The last set of patches have fixed the kernel panic issues I have been seeing on my side. Thank you&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="42422" author="yong.fan" created="Sat, 28 Jul 2012 07:22:29 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks James for caching the bug. The reason is found as following:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When AGL trigger osc_enqueue_base(), it may found the cached ldlm lock on client side without AGL RPC sending. Under such case, the AGL upcall() will change the cl_lock::cll_state from CLS_QUEUING to CLS_HELD directly by cl_wait_try(). But in cl_wait_try(), such case was ignored, so the original LASSERT() for cll_state checking is not correct.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The new patch set 4 has fixed the issue. If you have chance, please try such new patch. Thanks!&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
